data.content:
Program and Data
Program and Data refer to the executable code and associated information required by software to run and perform tasks.

Logical Address
A Logical Address is the address generated by a program, requiring translation to a physical address for memory access.<SEP>A logical address is the address generated by the CPU and composed of a page number and an offset within the page.<SEP>Logical address is the relative address assigned to each target module during compilation, starting from zero, and is used by processes during execution.<SEP>A logical address is a virtual address generated by a process, which is later mapped to a physical address.

Memory Management
Memory Management is a core function of operating systems, responsible for the allocation, deallocation, and efficient use of memory space in computers.

User Process
A User Process is an instance of a program in execution, requiring memory space managed by the operating system.

Virtual Storage Technology
Virtual Storage Technology enables logical memory expansion by using disk space to simulate additional main memory.

Operating System
The Operating System manages computer hardware and software resources, including memory allocation and address translation.<SEP>Operating System is a system software that manages computer hardware and software resources and provides common services for computer programs.<SEP>Operating system manages memory, maintains the page table, and oversees address translation via the MMU.<SEP>The operating system manages and controls processes using data structures like the Process Control Block.

Multi-Programming
Multi-Programming is the execution of multiple processes concurrently, requiring the operating system to manage memory allocation effectively.

Main Memory
Main Memory is the primary storage component of a computer where active programs and data are held for execution.<SEP>Main memory is the physical storage in which executable code and data are loaded for processing.

Physical Address
A Physical Address is the actual location in main memory where data is stored.<SEP>A physical address is the actual memory address in main memory, generated by combining a block number and a page offset.<SEP>The Physical Address is the actual location in main memory where a page resides.<SEP>Physical address refers to the actual memory location in main memory where data and instructions are stored and accessed.<SEP>A physical address is the actual location in main memory where data is stored.

Memory Space Recovery
Memory Space Recovery is the process by which the operating system reclaims memory after a process terminates.

Storage Protection
Storage Protection ensures that processes operate only within their designated memory space, preventing interference with other processes.

Memory Space Allocation
Memory Space Allocation refers to the process of assigning portions of memory to processes during runtime.

Memory Sharing
Memory Sharing allows multiple processes to access the same memory region under controlled conditions.<SEP>Memory sharing is a technique that allows multiple processes to share read-only memory regions, particularly for sharing executable code.

先进先出置换算法
First-In-First-Out (FIFO) page replacement algorithm selects the page that has been in memory the longest for eviction. It is simple to implement but suffers from performance issues and can produce Belady’s anomaly.

最佳置换算法
Optimal (OPT) page replacement algorithm selects the page that will not be used for the longest time in the future, or never used again, to minimize the page fault rate. This algorithm is theoretical and cannot be implemented in practice.

data.entity_name: 最近最久未使用置换算法
data.content:
最近最久未使用置换算法
Least Recently Used (LRU) page replacement algorithm selects the page that has not been accessed for the longest time. It performs well in practice but requires hardware support such as registers and stacks, which increases implementation cost.

时钟置换算法
Clock page replacement algorithm is a practical approximation of LRU. It uses a circular list of pages and a replacement pointer, along with access bits to track recent usage.

页面置换算法
Page replacement algorithm is a method used in operating systems to manage memory by selecting which page to evict when a new page needs to be loaded into memory and no free frames are available.<SEP>页面置换算法is a strategy used to determine which pages to replace when a page fault occurs; efficient algorithms reduce缺页率.

改进型时钟置换算法
Enhanced Clock page replacement algorithm improves upon the basic Clock algorithm by including a modify bit in addition to the access bit, allowing for better decision-making during page eviction.

访问位
Access bit is a flag associated with each page that is set to 1 when the page is accessed, used to track whether a page has been recently used.

修改位
Modify bit is a flag associated with each page that indicates whether the page has been modified since it was loaded into memory.

Belady异常
Belady’s anomaly is a phenomenon in which increasing the number of available frames in memory leads to an increase in the number of page faults, observed in FIFO page replacement.

硬件支持
Hardware support refers to specialized register and stack components required for efficient implementation of certain page replacement algorithms, particularly LRU.

缺页率
Page fault rate is the frequency of page faults occurring during process execution, a key performance metric for memory management algorithms.<SEP>缺页率is a key factor affecting virtual memory performance, representing the frequency of page faults during program execution.

2类页面
Class 2 page refers to a page with access bit A=0 and modify bit M=1, indicating it has not been accessed recently but has been modified, making it a secondary candidate for eviction.

物理块
Physical block refers to the unit of memory allocated to processes, also known as frame in virtual memory management.<SEP>物理块是内存中与页面大小相同的存储单元，用于分配和管理物理内存。<SEP>物理块refers to the fixed-size units of physical memory allocated to a process, determining how much memory is available for page storage.

3类页面
Class 3 page refers to a page with access bit A=1 and modify bit M=0, indicating it has been recently accessed but not modified, suggesting it may be accessed again soon.

1类页面
Class 1 page refers to a page with access bit A=0 and modify bit M=0, indicating it has not been accessed recently and has not been modified, making it the best candidate for eviction in the Enhanced Clock algorithm.

循环队列
Circular queue is a data structure used in the Clock algorithm to link pages in memory sequentially, allowing efficient traversal.

4类页面
Class 4 page refers to a page with access bit A=1 and modify bit M=1, indicating it has been recently accessed and modified, and thus is likely to be accessed again.

System Call
System Call is a request made by a program to the operating system to perform a specific operation, such as file access or memory management.

Disk File
Disk File is a file stored on a persistent storage device, which can be accessed and manipulated through file system operations.

File Content
File Content refers to the actual data stored within a disk file, which is only loaded into memory when accessed.

Process Virtual Address Space
Process Virtual Address Space is the range of memory addresses available to a running process, managed by the operating system.

Memory-Mapped Files
Memory-Mapped Files is a system call provided by the operating system that establishes a mapping relationship between a disk file and a process's virtual address space.

Virtual Memory
Virtual Memory is a memory management technique that provides an abstraction of a large, continuous address space to processes, enabling efficient use of physical memory and disk storage.<SEP>Virtual memory is a memory management technique that uses secondary storage to extend the apparent size of primary memory.<SEP>Virtual Memory is a memory management technique that uses secondary storage to extend the apparent size of physical memory.

Page
Page refers to a fixed-size block of memory, typically used in virtual memory and file mapping systems, usually 4KB in size.<SEP>A page is a fixed-size unit of logical address space within a process, corresponding to a page frame in physical memory.

Multiple Processes
Multiple Processes refers to the capability of an operating system to run more than one process concurrently, enabling resource sharing and multitasking.

Shared Memory
Shared Memory is a method by which multiple processes can access and communicate through a common memory area, often facilitated by memory mapping.

Performance Optimization
Performance Optimization is the process of improving the efficiency and speed of operations, often through mechanisms like memory mapping.

最佳适应算法
Best Fit algorithm orders free partitions by size in ascending order and allocates the smallest partition that fits the process requirement.

动态分区分配
Dynamic partition allocation, also known as variable partition allocation, is a memory management technique where memory is dynamically allocated to processes based on their actual needs, with partition sizes matching the process requirements exactly.<SEP>动态分区分配dynamically allocates memory partitions based on program size, reducing internal fragmentation compared to fixed partitioning.

外部碎片
External fragmentation refers to the small, unusable memory blocks that accumulate over time in memory, reducing memory utilization efficiency.

邻近适应算法
Next Fit algorithm, also known as circular first fit, continues searching from the last position where the previous search ended, aiming to reduce search time.

最坏适应算法
Worst Fit algorithm orders free partitions by size in descending order and allocates the largest available partition to the process.

首次适应算法
First Fit algorithm allocates the first available memory partition that meets the size requirement, with free partitions ordered by increasing address.

紧凑技术
Compaction technique is a method used to overcome external fragmentation by periodically moving and rearranging processes in memory to create larger contiguous blocks.

空闲分区链
The free partition chain is a data structure used in dynamic partition allocation to track and manage available memory partitions.

快速适应算法
Fast Fit algorithm organizes free partitions by common size classes, each with its own free partition chain for faster allocation.

内存利用率
Memory utilization refers to the efficiency with which available memory is used; it declines due to external fragmentation.

伙伴系统
The buddy system is a memory allocation method where all partitions are sized as powers of two, allowing efficient splitting and merging of blocks.

空闲分区链表
The free partition list is a data structure maintaining a list of available memory partitions for allocation, used in dynamic partition allocation.

哈希算法
Hash algorithm uses a hash function on free partition sizes to create a hash table, enabling fast lookup of corresponding free partition chains.

段页式存储管理
段页式存储管理是一种将分页存储管理和分段存储管理相结合的内存管理方法，通过段号、页号和页内偏移量实现逻辑地址到物理地址的转换。

分段存储管理
分段存储管理是一种将进程地址空间划分为逻辑段的内存管理方法，每段具有独立的段号和长度。<SEP>分段存储管理organizes memory into variable-sized segments based on logical program divisions, supporting user needs in programming and access.

分页存储管理
分页存储管理是一种将进程地址空间划分为固定大小页面的内存管理方法，内存以物理块为单位进行分配。

段表
段表是为每个进程建立的地址转换数据结构，记录各段的页表始址。<SEP>段表是每个进程维护的映射表，记录各段在内存中的始址和长度，每个段对应一个段表项。

页面
页面是分页存储管理中固定大小的存储单位，用于划分段和内存。

页表
页表是每个段中用于记录页号到物理块号映射的数据结构。

逻辑段
逻辑段是进程地址空间中按功能或逻辑划分的区域，每个段有唯一的段号。

段表寄存器
段表寄存器用于存储当前进程段表的起始地址，加速地址变换过程。<SEP>段表寄存器用于存放段表的始址F和段表长度M，是地址变换的关键硬件组件。

逻辑地址
逻辑地址由段号、页号和页内偏移量组成，用于表示进程中的地址。<SEP>逻辑地址is a reference to memory that is relative to the start of a program or module and needs to be converted to a physical address during execution.<SEP>An address generated by a CPU that refers to a location in virtual memory.

二维地址空间
二维地址空间指段页式存储管理中以段和页为维度的地址结构。<SEP>分段管理的地址空间是二维的，由段号和段内偏移量构成。

地址变换
地址变换是将逻辑地址转换为物理地址的过程，涉及段表和页表的查找。

页内偏移量
页内偏移量是页面内部的字节偏移，定位数据在页内的具体位置。

物理地址
物理地址是内存中实际存储位置的地址，通过逻辑地址计算获得。<SEP>An actual address on the main memory hardware used to access physical storage.<SEP>物理地址是通过段表始址与段内偏移量计算出的实际内存地址E = b + W。

段号
逻辑地址包含段号，用于定位进程的逻辑段。

页号
逻辑地址包含页号，用于定位段中的页面。

程序的链接与装入
程序的链接与装入is the process of transforming user source code into an executable program in memory, involving compilation, linking, and loading steps.

装入模块
装入模块is a complete executable unit formed by linking target modules and required library functions.

用户源程序
用户源程序refers to the original code written by a user that needs to be compiled and loaded into memory.

目标模块
目标模块are intermediate files generated by the compiler from source code, which need to be linked together.

创建进程
创建进程is the initial step of loading a program and data into memory to prepare it for execution.

链接
链接is the process of combining target modules and their required library functions into a single load module.

库函数
库函数are pre-written code segments that provide common functionality and are required by target modules.

编译
编译is the process of translating user source code into object code (target modules).

装入
装入is the process of moving a load module into memory so it can be executed.

可重定位装入
可重定位装入, also known as static relocation, involves loading a program at a location in memory and adjusting addresses at load time to reflect the actual memory location.

重定位
重定位refers to the adjustment of addresses in a program to reflect its actual memory location during loading or execution.

动态运行时装入
动态运行时装入, also known as dynamic relocation, delays address translation until execution time, allowing the program to be moved in memory during execution.

绝对装入
绝对装入is a loading method used in single-program environments where the program is loaded at a fixed memory address, with no address translation.

实际内存地址
实际内存地址is the absolute address in physical memory where a program or data item is stored.

重定位寄存器
重定位寄存器is a hardware register used in dynamic relocation to store the starting address of a loaded module.

静态链接
静态链接is a linking method where all modules are linked together before the program runs and remain fixed thereafter.

装入时动态链接
装入时动态链接is a linking method where linking occurs during loading, enabling on-demand linking and code sharing.

data.entity_name: 逻辑地址与实际内存地址
data.content:
逻辑地址与实际内存地址
逻辑地址与实际内存地址describes the distinction between relative addresses used in program code and their corresponding absolute addresses in physical memory.

运行时动态链接
运行时动态链接is a linking method where linking occurs only when a module is actually needed during program execution.

内存空间
内存空间is the physical memory available for storing and executing programs and data.

不连续的存储区
不连续的存储区is a memory allocation strategy where a program can be stored in non-adjacent memory regions.

程序和数据
程序和数据refers to the executable code and associated data that must be loaded into memory before a program can execute.

程序段的共享
程序段的共享allows multiple processes to use the same code segment in memory, reducing memory usage.

单道程序环境
单道程序环境refers to a computing environment where only one program runs at a time, suitable for absolute loading.

一次性
The characteristic of loading an entire program into memory in one go before execution begins.

空间局部性
The tendency for a program to access memory locations that are close to one another shortly after accessing a particular location.

data.entity_name: 内存-外存两级存储器结构
data.content:
内存-外存两级存储器结构
A two-level storage architecture combining main memory and secondary storage, enabling virtual memory implementation.

时间局部性
The tendency for a program to access the same instructions or data items repeatedly over a short period.

驻留性
The characteristic of a program remaining in memory throughout its execution without being swapped out.

传统存储管理方式
Traditional storage management methods are characterized by the need to load an entire job into memory at once and keep it resident until completion.

局部性原理
The principle that programs tend to access a relatively small portion of their address space at any given time, including time and space locality.<SEP>局部性原理explains that programs tend to access a limited set of memory locations repeatedly, influencing page fault frequency.

虚拟内存
Virtual memory is a memory management technique that provides an illusion of a large, contiguous memory space by using both physical memory and secondary storage.

虚拟存储器
A logical memory abstraction that appears larger than physical memory, created through virtual memory techniques.

虚拟性
The feature of virtual memory that logically expands the apparent size of main memory beyond its physical limits.

对换性
The ability to swap parts of a process between main memory and secondary storage during execution.

多次性
The ability to load a process into memory in multiple steps, rather than all at once.

请求段页式存储管理
A hybrid memory management method combining segmentation and paging, where segments are divided into pages and loaded on demand.

请求分页存储管理
A memory management technique where pages of a program are loaded into memory on demand when referenced.

页表机制
A data structure used to track the mapping between logical and physical addresses in page-based virtual memory.

请求分段存储管理
A memory management approach where segments of a program are loaded into memory only when needed.

段表机制
A data structure used in segment-based memory management to track the location and size of program segments.

Free Page List
The Free Page List stores unmodified pages that are not immediately written to disk, instead being placed at the end of the list for potential reuse.

Kernel-Used Page Frames
Kernel-used page frames are typically non-recyclable and remain allocated for system-level operations.

Kswapd
Kswapd is a Linux kernel daemon responsible for monitoring memory usage and initiating page frame recycling when free page thresholds are exceeded.

Modified Page List
The Modified Page List holds pages that have been modified and are pending eviction, temporarily stored in memory before being written to disk.

Memory Usage Threshold
The Memory Usage Threshold is a predefined limit that triggers the page frame recycling process when the number of free pages falls below it.

Page Frame Recycling
Page Frame Recycling refers to the process of reclaiming memory pages from processes when system memory is insufficient, primarily targeting pages used by user processes.

Page Buffering Algorithm
The Page Buffering Algorithm enhances the original page replacement algorithm by introducing linked lists for unmodified and modified pages to reduce the overhead of page swapping.

User-Process Page Frames
User-process page frames are generally recyclable and can be reclaimed when needed to free up memory.

中断机构
Hardware or software mechanism that signals the operating system when a required memory page is not in physical memory.

对换区
A designated area on secondary storage used for swapping out inactive memory pages.

地址变换机构
A component responsible for translating logical addresses into physical addresses in memory management.<SEP>地址变换机构负责从逻辑地址转换为物理地址，包括越界检查与物理地址计算。

外存
Secondary storage (e.g., hard disk) used for long-term storage of data and programs.

内存
Main memory (RAM) is the primary volatile storage for a computer system.

User Area
The User Area is the portion of memory available for user programs and, in single continuous allocation, holds only one user program at a time.

Memory Utilization
Memory Utilization refers to the efficiency of memory usage, which is very low in single continuous allocation due to the exclusive occupation of the user area by a single program.

Memory Protection
Memory Protection is a mechanism that prevents one program from accessing another program's memory, which is not required in this method due to the single-user model.<SEP>Memory protection ensures that each process has a separate memory space and prevents interference between the operating system and user processes, as well as between different user processes.

External Fragmentation
External Fragmentation refers to the situation where free memory is scattered in small blocks, but this method avoids it by requiring a single contiguous block.<SEP>External fragmentation refers to the inefficient use of memory space due to non-contiguous allocation; it is not produced in page-based management.<SEP>External fragmentation is the free memory scattered in small, non-contiguous blocks, which does not occur in fixed partition allocation.

System Area
The System Area is the part of memory reserved for the operating system and is typically located in the low-address portion.

Internal Fragmentation
Internal Fragmentation occurs when a program does not fully utilize its allocated memory, leaving unused space within the allocated block.<SEP>Internal fragmentation occurs when pages are not fully utilized, leading to unused space within allocated page frames.<SEP>Internal fragmentation is the wasted memory space within a partition when a program is smaller than the partition size, leading to inefficient memory utilization.

User Program
A User Program is a single application running in the user area that monopolizes the entire user memory space in this allocation method.<SEP>A user program is a software application executed by a computer, requiring memory allocation for operation.

Single Continuous Allocation
Single Continuous Allocation is a memory management method where memory is divided into a system area and a user area, with the user area occupied by only one user program at a time.<SEP>Single continuous allocation is a memory management technique that allocates the entire memory space to a single user program.

Page Frame
A page frame is a fixed-size block in physical memory used to store a page of a process.<SEP>A Page Frame is a fixed-size block of physical memory used to store a page of virtual memory.

Logical Address Space
The logical address space is the address space as viewed by a process, divided into pages of equal size.

Basic Page Storage Management
Basic page storage management is a memory management technique that divides physical memory into fixed-size blocks called page frames, and logically divides the process address space into pages of the same size.

Physical Block
A physical block refers to a fixed-size segment of main memory used in page-based allocation.

Page Size
Page size is the fixed size of a page or page frame and should be a power of 2 for efficient address translation.

Page Number
A page number is an index assigned to each page in the logical address space, starting from zero.

Address Structure
The address structure in paging consists of a page number and a page offset within the page.

Page Table Length
Page table length is the number of entries in a process's page table, used to check for address bound violations.

Page Frame Number
A page frame number is the index of a page frame in physical memory, starting from zero.

Page Table
A page table is a data structure that maps each page of a process to its corresponding physical page frame, and contains entries with page numbers and block numbers.<SEP>The Page Table is a critical data structure that maps virtual page numbers to physical frame numbers in memory.<SEP>Page table is a data structure maintained by the operating system to map logical addresses to physical addresses.

Page Table Register
The page table register (PTR) stores the starting address and length of the page table in memory.

Page Table Entry
A page table entry contains the mapping from a logical page number to a physical block number.<SEP>A Page Table Entry contains metadata about a virtual page, including status, access, modification, and external storage address information.<SEP>A page table entry is a component in a process's page table that maps a virtual page to a physical page.

Page Offset
The page offset is the displacement within a page, used to locate specific bytes within a page.

Fast Table
The fast table is another term for the TLB, used to accelerate address translation.

Translation Lookaside Buffer
The translation lookaside buffer (TLB) is a high-speed cache that stores recently accessed page table entries to speed up address translation.<SEP>The Translation Lookaside Buffer is a high-speed cache that stores recent page table entries to speed up address translation.

Outer Page Table
The outer page table, also known as the page directory, contains the base addresses of second-level page tables.

Two-Level Page Table
A two-level page table is a hierarchical structure used to reduce the memory overhead of large page tables by splitting them into a second-level table.

Page Directory Register
The page directory register stores the base address of the outer page table or page directory.

Basic Address Transformation Mechanism
The basic address transformation mechanism converts logical addresses into physical addresses using a page table.

Slow Table
The slow table refers to the main memory page table, used when the TLB does not contain the required mapping.

Page Directory Number
The page directory number is the index used to access the outer page table to locate the second-level page table.

Second-Level Page Number
The second-level page number is used as an index into the second-level page table to find the physical block number.

Page Directory
The page directory is another term for the outer page table used in two-level paging to manage second-level page tables.

Page Directory Base Address Register
The page directory base address register stores the starting address of the page directory in memory.

Multi-Level Page Table
A multi-level page table is an extension of the two-level approach, used to manage very large address spaces by further dividing the outer page table.

Physical Block Number
A physical address is created by combining the physical block number and the page offset.<SEP>The Physical Block Number identifies the specific frame in physical memory where a virtual page is stored.

Page Fault Rate
Page fault rate is the frequency with which a process accesses a page not in memory, influenced by the size of the resident set.

Resident Set Size
Resident set size is the set of page frames allocated to a process in memory, directly affecting the number of processes that can reside in memory and their performance.

Fixed Allocation
Fixed allocation is a memory management strategy where each process is assigned a fixed number of physical page frames, which remains constant during execution.

Page Frame Allocation
Page frame allocation refers to the process by which the operating system assigns a number of page frames to a specific process in a paged virtual memory system.

Global Replacement
Global replacement is a page replacement strategy where any page in memory, regardless of which process it belongs to, can be selected for replacement.

Multiprogramming Degree
Multiprogramming degree refers to the number of processes that can be simultaneously in memory, which increases as the resident set size decreases.

Memory Allocation Strategy
Memory allocation strategy determines how physical memory blocks are assigned to processes in a request-paging system.

Variable Allocation
Variable allocation is a memory management strategy that allows the number of physical page frames assigned to a process to change dynamically during execution.

Local Replacement
Local replacement is a page replacement strategy where only pages belonging to the same process that experienced a page fault are considered for replacement.

Average Allocation Algorithm
Average allocation algorithm distributes available physical page frames equally among all running processes.

Variable Allocation Global Replacement
Variable allocation global replacement allows dynamic adjustment of page frames and permits replacement from any process in memory.

Preloading Page Strategy
Preloading page strategy involves predicting future page accesses and loading them into memory in advance.

Variable Allocation Local Replacement
Variable allocation local replacement allows dynamic adjustment of page frames, with replacement limited to the process's own pages.

Proportional Allocation Algorithm
Proportional allocation algorithm assigns physical page frames to processes based on their size or resource requirements.

Fixed Allocation Local Replacement
Fixed allocation local replacement combines fixed page frame assignment with replacement limited to the process's own pages.

Priority Allocation Algorithm
Priority allocation algorithm assigns more page frames to high-priority or urgent processes.

Demand Page Strategy
Demand page strategy involves loading a page into memory only when it is requested by a process during execution.

Swap Area
Swap area is a dedicated region of secondary storage used to hold pages that have been swapped out of main memory.

Physical Page Frame
Physical page frame is a block of physical memory used to store a page of virtual memory.

Disk I/O Speed
Disk I/O speed refers to the rate at which data can be read from or written to the disk, affecting page loading performance.

Demand Paging
Demand paging is a memory management technique where pages are loaded into memory only when they are needed.

File Area
File area is a region of secondary storage used to store files and program images.

Page Fault
Page fault occurs when a process attempts to access a page not currently present in physical memory.

UNIX Method
UNIX method is a page loading strategy where unused pages are loaded from the file area, while previously run and swapped-out pages are loaded from the swap area.

Request-Paging System
Request-paging system is a virtual memory management system where pages are loaded into memory only when accessed, supporting dynamic memory allocation and demand-based loading.

Access Field A
The Access Field A records how often a page has been accessed or the time elapsed since its last access.

Modify Bit M
The Modify Bit M indicates whether a page has been modified in memory since it was loaded.

Request Paging System
The Request Paging System is an advanced memory management technique built on the basic paging system, enabling virtual memory by supporting demand paging and page replacement.

Status Bit P
The Status Bit P indicates whether a page is currently loaded into main memory or not.

Basic Paging System
The Basic Paging System is a foundational memory management method that divides memory into fixed-size pages and frames for efficient memory allocation.

External Storage Address
The External Storage Address specifies the location on secondary storage where a page is stored when not in memory.

Page Replacement Algorithm
The Page Replacement Algorithm determines which page in memory should be replaced when a new page needs to be loaded and no free page frames are available.

Page Fault Handler
The Page Fault Handler is a component of the operating system that manages the interrupt process triggered when a requested page is not in memory.

Blocking Queue
The Blocking Queue holds processes that are waiting for a page to be loaded into memory.

Ready Queue
The Ready Queue contains processes that are ready to execute once they obtain required resources.

Address Translation Mechanism
The Address Translation Mechanism converts virtual addresses to physical addresses using the page table and translation lookaside buffer (TLB).

Page Fault Interrupt
The Page Fault Interrupt occurs when a requested page is not present in main memory, triggering a system intervention to load it.

Virtual Address
The Virtual Address is the logical address generated by a process that is later translated into a physical address.

Page Content
The Page Content refers to the actual data stored within a virtual page when loaded into memory.

Virtual Address Space
Virtual address space is the unified logical address space created by the linker, starting from zero, used during program execution.

Memory Management Unit
Memory Management Unit (MMU) is a hardware component that assists in translating logical addresses into physical addresses.<SEP>The memory management unit is responsible for translating logical addresses to physical addresses and performing bounds checking.

Address Relocation
Address relocation is the process of converting logical addresses into physical addresses during program loading.

Process
Process is an executing instance of a program that uses logical addresses and relies on address mapping for memory access.<SEP>A process is an instance of a program in execution, which may access shared code and maintain private data during runtime.

Linker
Linker is a program that combines multiple target modules into a single executable program by assigning unified logical addresses.

Compiler
Compiler is a program that translates source code into target modules, assigning logical addresses starting from zero.

Memory Partition
Memory partition is a fixed-size area of memory allocated to hold a single job in the fixed partition allocation method.

Partition Usage Table
Partition usage table is a data structure used to track the allocation and status of memory partitions for easier assignment and recovery.

User Memory Space
User memory space is the portion of computer memory allocated to user processes, which is divided into fixed partitions in this method.

Fixed Partition Allocation
Fixed partition allocation is a simple memory management technique in multiprogramming systems that divides user memory into fixed-size partitions, each holding one job at a time.<SEP>Fixed partition allocation divides memory into fixed-size partitions, each allocated to a user program.

Partition Size Equal
Partition size equal refers to a method of dividing memory into partitions of identical size.

Partition Size Unequal
Partition size unequal refers to a method where memory is divided into partitions of different sizes.

Job
Job refers to a program or task being processed in a multiprogramming system, which is loaded into a single fixed memory partition.

存储管理方式
存储管理方式describes the methods used by operating systems to manage memory resources, evolving from simple to advanced techniques.

内存分配与回收
内存分配与回收refers to the process of allocating and reclaiming memory space in computer systems, evolving with advancements in operating systems.

页式存储管理
页式存储管理is a memory management technique that divides memory into fixed-size pages, allowing efficient use of non-contiguous memory blocks.

离散分配方式
离散分配方式allocates memory in non-contiguous blocks, improving memory utilization, exemplified by page-based management.

固定分区分配
固定分区分配divides memory into fixed-size partitions, allowing multiple programs to run concurrently but leading to internal fragmentation.

单一连续分配
单一连续分配is a memory management method where a single program occupies the entire memory space, used in early single-task operating systems.

操作系统
操作系统is a system software that manages computer hardware and software resources, enabling the evolution of memory management techniques.

页面大小
页面大小refers to the size of each memory page, influencing the frequency of page faults; larger pages generally result in lower缺页率.

data.entity_name: 已修改换出页面的链表
data.content:
已修改换出页面的链表
已修改换出页面的链表is a data structure used to track pages that have been modified and evicted, helping reduce disk I/O.

磁盘I/O次数
磁盘I/O次数refers to the number of input/output operations performed on disk, which can be reduced by optimizing page management.

物理块数
物理块数denotes the number of physical memory blocks allocated to a process, with higher allocation leading to lower缺页率.

程序编制方法
程序编制方法refers to how a program is written, particularly its locality characteristics, which affect缺页率.

写回磁盘的频率
写回磁盘的频率indicates how often modified pages are written back to disk, a factor affecting system performance.

Continuous Allocation Method
Continuous allocation method refers to the process of assigning a contiguous block of memory space to a user program.

Memory Space
Memory space refers to the area of computer memory available for storing data and instructions.

Dynamic Partition Allocation
Dynamic partition allocation assigns memory partitions of varying sizes based on the program's requirements.

抖动
抖动refers to the frequent page swapping in memory management, where pages are rapidly exchanged between main memory and secondary storage, leading to system inefficiency.

页面置换
页面置换is the process of replacing pages in main memory with pages from secondary storage to manage virtual memory.

进程
进程is a running instance of a program, which accesses memory pages and relies on proper memory management for efficient execution.

缺页
缺页occurs when a process attempts to access a page not currently in main memory, triggering a page fault and resulting in page loading from secondary storage.

工作集
工作集is the set of pages a process accesses within a specific time interval, representing the pages likely to be accessed in the near future.

驻留集
驻留集is the set of pages currently present in main memory for a process, which should be large enough to contain the working set.

Lower Limit Register
The lower limit register stores the minimum address accessible by a user process in main memory.

Upper Limit Register
The upper limit register stores the maximum address accessible by a user process in main memory.

Bound Address Register
The bound address register, also known as the limit register, stores the maximum logical address a process can access.

Relocation Register
The relocation register, also known as the base address register, holds the starting physical address of a process.

CPU
CPU is the central processing unit that manages instruction execution and performs address comparisons for memory access.

Privileged Instruction
Privileged instructions are special machine instructions that can only be executed by the operating system kernel and are used to load critical registers.

Operating System Kernel
The operating system kernel is the core component of the operating system that manages system resources and can execute privileged instructions.

Shared Code Area
The shared code area is the physical or logical memory region containing code that is shared across multiple processes.

Physical Page Number
The physical page number is the actual memory location where a page of code or data resides in physical memory.

Private Data Area
A private data area is a memory region allocated per process to hold local data that may be modified during code execution.

Reentrant Code
Reentrant code, also known as pure code, is executable code that can be safely accessed by multiple processes simultaneously and must not be modified by any process.

Read-Only Regions
Read-only regions are memory areas that can be shared among processes without modification.

Segment Table Entry
A segment table entry is a component in a process's segment table that points to the start address of a shared segment.

Shared Code Segment
The shared code segment is the segment in memory containing code that is shared among multiple processes.

Code Sharing
Code sharing is the practice of allowing multiple processes to execute the same code segment from a shared memory region, improving memory efficiency and system performance.

Segmentation System
The segmentation system is a memory management technique that divides memory into variable-sized segments, managed via segment tables.

Execution Time
Execution time refers to the period during which a program is actively running and modifying data in memory, particularly when executing reentrant code.

Paging System
The paging system is a memory management technique that uses fixed-size pages and page tables to map virtual addresses to physical addresses.

逻辑地址空间
逻辑地址空间是用户进程的虚拟地址空间，被划分为大小不等的段。

分页管理方式
分页管理方式是从计算机角度设计的内存管理方法，主要目的是提高内存利用率，对用户不可见。

分段管理方式
分段管理方式考虑了用户和程序员的需求，支持方便编程、信息保护与共享、动态增长及动态链接等功能。

逻辑地址结构
逻辑地址结构由段号S与段内偏移量W组成，由用户显式提供。

段
段是逻辑地址空间的划分单位，每段从0开始编址并分配连续的地址空间，段内连续但段间不要求连续。

可重入代码
可重入代码是一种允许多个进程同时安全访问的代码，也称为纯代码。

段内偏移量W
段内偏移量W是逻辑地址中表示段内位置的偏移值，用于定位段内具体地址。

段号S
段号S是逻辑地址中表示段的编号，用于在段表中查找对应段表项。

共享段表
共享段表用于管理多个进程共享的段，每个共享段在表中有一个表项。

存取控制保护
存取控制保护是分段管理中用于保护段的一种方法，控制对段的访问权限。

地址越界保护
地址越界保护是分段管理中用于防止非法访问的保护机制，检测段号或偏移量是否超出范围。

虚拟地址空间
分段管理方式以用户和程序员需求为核心，构建二维的虚拟地址空间。

Process Memory Image
The process memory image is the in-memory representation of a program when loaded for execution, consisting of various segments including code, data, heap, stack, and process control block.

Executable Program File
An executable program file is a file stored on disk that contains machine code and is loaded into memory to create a process.

Data Segment
The data segment stores data that the program manipulates during execution, including global and static variables.

Code Segment
The code segment contains the binary machine code of a program, is read-only, and can be shared among multiple processes.

Heap
The heap is a memory region used for dynamic memory allocation during runtime, managed via functions like malloc and free.

Process Control Block
The Process Control Block (PCB) is a system-resident data structure used by the operating system to store and manage information about a process.

Stack
The stack is a memory region used to manage function calls, growing downward from the highest address in user space.

Malloc Function
The malloc function is a standard C library function used to dynamically allocate memory on the heap.

Free Function
The free function is a standard C library function used to de-allocate memory previously allocated with malloc.
